            <h1>FIRST Robotics Competition</h1>
        </div>

     <p1>  The FIRST Robotics Competition (FRC) is an international robotics program for high school students.
In FRC, teams design, build, and program large industrial-style robots.
Each season begins with the release of a new challenge game.
Teams have a limited amount of time to design and build their robot.
The robot must complete tasks on a full-size competition field.
FRC robots are much larger and more powerful than FTC or FLL robots.
Students use advanced materials such as aluminum, steel, and pneumatic systems.
Programming is usually done in Java, C++, or Python.
FRC teaches students how software, hardware, and electronics work together.
Engineering design is a major focus of the competition.
Teams must carefully plan before building begins.
Prototyping helps teams test ideas early.
Problem solving is constant throughout the build season.
Teams often redesign parts to improve performance.
Strategy plays a crucial role during matches.
Robots compete in alliances, requiring teamwork between teams.
FRC competitions are fast-paced and intense.
Students must react quickly to unexpected issues.
Judging is based on robot performance, teamwork, and outreach.
Teams are expected to document their design process.
FRC emphasizes values such as Gracious Professionalism and cooperation.
Mentors support students without doing the work for them.
Students gain hands-on experience with real engineering tools.
Time management becomes critical due to tight deadlines.
Participants develop leadership and communication skills.
FRC introduces students to real-world engineering challenges.
The program connects students with industry professionals.
Many students discover future career paths through FRC.
FRC builds confidence through hard work and achievement.
Overall, FRC provides a powerful and realistic engineering experience.
        </p1> 
        <h1>how to make your own team</h1>
        <p1>Creating an FRC team begins with gathering motivated high school students.
A strong team includes members interested in engineering, programming, and design.
Finding committed adult mentors is essential for success.
Mentors provide guidance and technical knowledge.
The team must register officially on the FIRST website.
After registration, the team receives a unique team number.
Choosing a team name helps build identity and pride.
Teams need a suitable workspace with enough room for large robots.
Safety is extremely important in an FRC workspace.
Teams must acquire tools and machinery for building.
Funding is a major requirement for FRC teams.
Sponsorships help cover costs such as parts and competition fees.
Teams should begin planning as soon as the game is released.
Understanding the rules early helps guide design decisions.
Strategy discussions help determine robot priorities.
Designs should be tested using prototypes.
Building and programming happen simultaneously.
Regular testing helps improve robot performance.
Teams must document their engineering process.
Clear communication helps avoid mistakes.
Assigning roles improves efficiency and organization.
Regular meetings keep the team on schedule.
Students should learn to manage time effectively.
Challenges should be solved collaboratively.
Mistakes provide valuable learning opportunities.
Practice matches help prepare for competitions.
Respect and teamwork are core values of FRC.
Competitions provide feedback and inspiration.
Students grow through responsibility and leadership.
Creating an FRC team offers an unforgettable STEM experience.</p1>
